MYCOBACTERIUM ULCERANS - IVORY COAST
************************************
[What follows are two postings on _M. ulcerans_ the causative agent of
Buruli ulcers. The first is a copiously edited version [reduced by 50% to
include facts] of a Reuters story and the second was provided by Steve
Berger upon our request. He used the GIDEON software to obtain current
information on _M. ulcerans_ . The information content between the two
postings is not terribly different but the style, innuendo and "scare
index" of the two information packets couldn't differ more widely. To
quote my brother, who is visiting, the first article is the "stuff of the
Saturday Night Horror Show." The gap between the headline grabbing article
probably written by an aspiring journalist and the clinical and
epidemiological summary provided by Steve Berger shows just how complex the
risk communication aspect of emerging disease will prove to be. - Mod. pc]

[1]
Date: Tue, 22 Jul 1997 16:42:04 -1000
From: dono@hgea.org (Dorothy and Norman Hallett)
Via: Reuters
Abidjan, Ivory Coast -- A flesh-rotting germ lurking in the soil of Africa
has been stirred up by destruction of the tropical forests and is attacking
people as never before, doctors say.
Buruli, a virulent African version of a flesh-eating bacterium that
surfaced in Western hospitals in the 1990s, strips away skin by destroying
blood vessels with toxins to expose huge areas of gangrenous flesh.

"It was probably already there but environmental disaster has awakened it,"
he [who? - mod. pc] said after taking WHO director Hiroshi Nakajima on a
June fact-finding tour of clinics.
The total number of cases is unknown but European and African researchers
want Buruli ulcer put on WHO's top category for tropical disease research
funding, alongside malaria, sleeping sickness and yellow fever. In Ivory
Coast alone, where a world symposium on Buruli ulcer is planned for
February 1998, the bug has infected 6,000 people -- from just two when it
began to emerge 15 years ago following a spate of post independence dam
building and logging. Buruli ulcer tends to attack women working fields
around villages, along with their young children, who play in soil nearby.
Dr. Jean Marie-Kanga, chief dermatologist at Abidjan's university hospital
said the antibiotic Rifampicin used in leprosy treatment killed the
bacteria in test tubes. "There is no treatment for humans even though it
works in vitro," he said at his laboratory, where U.S.-based Centers for
Disease Control researchers are lending a hand.

--
Dorothy and Norman Hallett
dono@hgea.org (Dorothy and Norman Hallett)
