[2]
Date: Thu, 24 Jul 1997 14:29:17 -0600 (MDT)
From: "Dr. Steve Berger" <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Mycobacterium ulcerans (formerly Mycobacterium buruli) is a slowly-growing
non-chromogenic bacterium that is negative for most of the classical
in-vitro tests used for mycobacteria: Growth at 45 C; Catalase; Nitrate
reduction; Pyrazinamidase; Arylsulfatase; Tween hydrolysis; Growth in 5%
NaCl; Iron uptake; and growth at 37 C.
Human disease is probably acquired from direct contact with water or
vegetation. Following
an incubation period of 3 weeks to 3 months, the patient develops a slowly
growing, painless
ulcerative nodule with undermined edges. Lymphadenopathy is usually not
present. In most
cases, a single leg lesion involving the extensor surface is present;
however, the face and trunk may be involved in children. Typical therapy
for adults consists of excision as needed; and a combination of rifampicin
and amikacin (or ethambutol and sulfamethoxazole/ rimethoprim) for 6 weeks.
Children may be given rifampicin 20 mg/kg/day with amikacin 7.5 mg/kg q12h
X 6w.
Mycobacterium ulcerans infection is known as 'Buruli ulcer' and was first
described in
1948 in Australia. The disease is found in Africa (and named for Buruli
County, Uganda),
Latin America, New Guinea, Malaysia, Sumatra and Australia.
In Australia, the infection is known as 'Bairnsdale ulcer' and is endemic
to the northern territory and east coast - Victoria (East Gippsland,
Western Port and Mornington Pennisular). 25 cases were reported from
Phillip Island (Victoria) during 1993 to 1994 - apparently acquired from
water used to irrigate a golf course. 45 cases were reported from the
Western Port and Mornington Peninsular regions of Southern Victoria during
1980 to 1995. In nearby Papua New Guinea, the disease is most common in
East Sepik and Kumusi River region.
GIDEON also found another other cause of 'jungle rot':
By the way, Buruli ulcer should not be confused with Tropical phagedenic
ulcer. The latter is ascribed to dual infection by bacteria in the genera
Fusobacterium and Borrelia and is
acquired through minor skin trauma in tropical areas. The condition is
characterized by a deep, painful, foul-smelling ulcer (usually of the leg)
with undermined edges. Secondary
infection by other microbes may follow. Therapy consists of Systemic
penicillin; with excision/debridement as necessary.
